<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>UnderToad</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Lurker<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Aug 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>omigod i never realized how many ppl were totally clueless about how aggro works<br />
ok let me try to clear some things up<br />
keep in mind i dont have access to game code so i am going by observation only<br />
that means im really only guessing :P<br />
<br />
<br />
first off aggro can be very variable<br />
there are many many actions that will modify aggro<br />
<br />
the best example is sitting<br />
everyone knows how sitting will often put u to the top of the hate list and get u clobbered<br />
<br />
touching a mob with a weapon also modifies aggro<br />
this is the single greatest thing tanks have going for them<br />
<br />
proximity modifies aggro<br />
the closer u are to a mob the more it hates u and the madder it gets for each action u take against it<br />
there is a big difference in the aggro u generate if u are within melee range or not<br />
<br />
now this is an important one for us<br />
ur original position on the mobs hate list affects aggro <br />
if ur one of the first ones to aggro it ur gonna pop to the top of the hate list more easily<br />
since we must malos/slow mobs asap this affects us a lot<br />
<br />
so ...<br />
whats the formula for causing urself to generate max aggro on any given mob?<br />
be the first one to cast on it and stand right next to it and melee<br />
how many shamans in game u figure fit that profile? :P<br />
<br />
<br />
those were modifiers to aggro<br />
like a multipier<br />
now we are gonna talk about hate itself<br />
hate is an actual number stored in the mobs *brain* that determines how much it *hates* each person that has aggroed it<br />
<br />
basically theres 4 diff types of hate (that i can think of off the top of my head anyway :P)<br />
<br />
theres dmg<br />
for each point of dmg that u do to a mob u generate x hate<br />
<br />
theres healing<br />
for each point of healing u do u generate y amount of hate toward all mobs that are in range<br />
<br />
theres buffing<br />
normally hate from buffing is very small but it can add up<br />
try casting an mgb during a pull :P<br />
<br />
finally theres innate spell hate<br />
each spell u cast on a mob has a base amount of hate that it generates<br />
this hate can be modified by many things<br />
i covered several above but an important modifier is whether the spell was resisted or not<br />
in general if a spell is resisted it will generate more hate than if it actually lands<br />
<br />
<br />
some spells generate a low amount of hate and others generate a huge amount of hate<br />
some spells also have an aggro modifier built into them<br />
our poison dots are one of these spells<br />
poison dots (and fire dots too just ask any druid :P) generate more hate than the amount of dmg that they do<br />
thats just the way they are coded <br />
it has always been that way (at least for the last 3 years)<br />
<br />
<br />
poison dots had mega aggro before they made tash use poison counters<br />
and our disease dots have counters too but they are low aggro ...<br />
so i never bought the theory that it is the poison counters that make these dots have so much aggro<br />
its just the way they were coded from the begining<br />
fire and poison dots have huge aggro period<br />
just like stun and slow and cripple and snare are high aggro ...</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Undertoad Deathwish (i always get MY wish)<br />
65 Shammy Bertox</div>
	
	
